Thinking about how Greeks believed the planets will one day return to their original positions, realigned with Cancer (the summer solstice) and the world will restart from the beginning again. Leibniz wrote an essay on it too which *literally* talks about Borges' "Babel library".
"I myself, for example, would be living in a city called Hannover located on the Leine river, occupied with the history of Brunswick, and writing letters to the same friends with the same meaning."

One of the most insane things no one talks about is how St. John the Baptist is going to be the replacement of Satan in his role as an angel at the left hand of the Lord and that's why the summer solstice of Cancer and Janus' crying face is associated with him. It's just so wild.
My grandfather goes to bed at eight in the evening with the sundown and wakes up 4 in the morning to eat baked goods with coffee. Aligned with the earth and the seasons.

Lord of Spirits podcast on St. John is genuinely groundbreaking stuff and then R. Guenon in "Symbols of Sacred Science" perfectly explains the cosmic roles of the solstices and it just makes everything fit perfectly

Does anyone else's finance guy friend tell him how if you melt old coins the metal is going to be worth more than if you melted newer coins, even if their monetary value is supposed to be higher and this is a sign of inflation and why the banking system will go down in ~30 years?

Genuinely one of the most mindblowing things to me and I guess the distinction between metal value and monetary value is analogical to the distinction between a word's etymology and dictionary definition, one is the "true root" and the other is the current consensus. Fascinating.

Dr. Ray Peat mentioned medicine/pharma is surprisingly fragile and if ~3-5% of the population suddenly quits the medical system of drugs, doctors, etc. the entire thing goes down the drain, I wonder if part of the reason for Covid's sudden end was a close call with this scenario.

I believe similarly if a very small number of people lose trust in a bank and withdraw their money, the bank basically fails immediately and if 5% of people globally stop using the banking system it also instantly falls apart. I think we underestimate the institutions' fragility.

Along a similar vein, I recall Contrary Pancake had a post about how in 2011 the US military was forced to temporarily secretly seize control of the civil government as to prevent a war and occupation of Iran that could have lead to the army's disestablishment as an organization.
